[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] In probability theory and statistics, the **characteristic function** of any real-valued random variable completely defines its probability distribution.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] If a random variable admits a probability density function, then the characteristic function is the Fourier transform (with sign reversal) of the probability density function.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Thus it provides an alternative route to analytical results compared with working directly with probability density functions or cumulative distribution functions.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] There are particularly simple results for the characteristic functions of distributions defined by the weighted sums of random variables.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] In addition to univariate distributions, characteristic functions can be defined for vector- or matrix-valued random variables, and can also be extended to more generic cases.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The characteristic function always exists when treated as a function of a real-valued argument, unlike the moment-generating function.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] There are relations between the behavior of the characteristic function of a distribution and properties of the distribution, such as the existence of moments and the existence of a density function.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The characteristic function is a way to describe a random variable X.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] a function of t, determines the behavior and properties of the probability distribution of X.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] It is equivalent to a probability density function (if it exists) or cumulative distribution function, in the sense that knowing one of these functions allows computation of the others, but they provide different insights into the features of the random variable.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] In particular cases, one or another of these equivalent functions may be easier to represent in terms of simple standard functions.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] If a random variable admits a density function, then the characteristic function is its Fourier dual, in the sense that each of them is a Fourier transform of the other.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Note however that the characteristic function of a distribution is well defined for all real values of t, even when the moment-generating function is not well defined for all real values of t.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The characteristic function approach is particularly useful in analysis of linear combinations of independent random variables: a classical proof of the Central Limit Theorem uses characteristic functions and Lévy's continuity theorem.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Another important application is to the theory of the decomposability of random variables.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The integrals are in the Riemann–Stieltjes sense.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The last equality holds if $f_{X}$ exists, which then implies that $\varphi _{X}$ is its Fourier transform with sign reversal in the complex exponential.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The convention for the constant appearing in the above definition differs from the usual convention for the Fourier transform.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] For example, some authors define $\varphi _{X}=\left[e^{-2\pi itX}\right]$ , which is essentially a change of parameter.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Other notation may be encountered in the literature: ${\hat {p}}$ as the characteristic function for a probability measure p , or ${\hat {f}}$ as the characteristic function corresponding to a density f .
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The notion of characteristic functions generalizes to multivariate random variables and more complicated random elements.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The argument of the characteristic function will always belong to the continuous dual of the space where the random variable X takes its values.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Oberhettinger (1973) provides extensive tables of characteristic functions.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The bijection stated above between probability distributions and characteristic functions is *sequentially continuous*.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] That is, whenever a sequence of distribution functions *Fj*(*x*) converges (weakly) to some distribution *F*(*x*), the corresponding sequence of characteristic functions *φ**j*(*t*) will also converge, and the limit *φ*(*t*) will correspond to the characteristic function of law F.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] This theorem can be used to prove the law of large numbers and the central limit theorem.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] There is a one-to-one correspondence between cumulative distribution functions and characteristic functions, so it is possible to find one of these functions if we know the other.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] The formula in the definition of characteristic function allows us to compute φ when we know the distribution function F (or density f).
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] If, on the other hand, we know the characteristic function φ and want to find the corresponding distribution function, then one of the following **inversion theorems** can be used.
