[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] This is the characteristic function of the standard Cauchy distribution: thus, the sample mean has the same distribution as the population itself.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] As a further example, suppose X follows a Gaussian distribution i.e. $X\sim {\mathcal {N}}(\mu ,\sigma ^{2})$ .
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] A similar calculation shows $\operatorname {E} \left[X^{2}\right]=\mu ^{2}+\sigma ^{2}$ and is easier to carry out than applying the definition of expectation and using integration by parts to evaluate $\operatorname {E} \left[X^{2}\right]$ .
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Characteristic functions can be used as part of procedures for fitting probability distributions to samples of data.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Cases where this provides a practicable option compared to other possibilities include fitting the stable distribution since closed form expressions for the density are not available which makes implementation of maximum likelihood estimation difficult.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Estimation procedures are available which match the theoretical characteristic function to the empirical characteristic function, calculated from the data.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] (1975) and Heathcote (1977) provide some theoretical background for such an estimation procedure.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] In addition, Yu (2004) describes applications of empirical characteristic functions to fit time series models where likelihood procedures are impractical.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] Empirical characteristic functions have also been used by Ansari et al.
[src:probability-theory/characteristic-function-probability-theory] (2020) for training generative adversarial networks.
